The Quick Ratio formula is:

\[
\text{Quick Ratio} = \frac{\text{Quick Assets}}{\text{Current Liabilities}}
\]

Quick Assets are current assets excluding inventory, basically:

\[
\text{Quick Assets} = \text{Cash on Hand} + \text{Bank Deposits} + \text{Interest Receivable} + \text{Accounts Receivable}
\]

Given data at the end of the reporting period (2024-02-05):

- Cash on Hand = 3,537,257.19
- Bank Deposits = 4,579,000.00
- Interest Receivable = 14,869.76
- Accounts Receivable = 1,716,911.17
- Inventory = 174,000.00
- Total Current Liabilities = 967,271.87

Step 1: Calculate Quick Assets

\[
3,537,257.19 + 4,579,000.00 + 14,869.76 + 1,716,911.17 = \\
3,537,257.19 + 4,579,000 + 14,869.76 + 1,716,911.17 = 9,848,038.12
\]

Step 2: Calculate Quick Ratio

\[
\frac{9,848,038.12}{967,271.87} \approx 10.18
\]

So, the Quick Ratio is approximately 10.18.
